Almost all newborn CNS tissues examined, except spinal cord sections, reacted with LPA and MAA, indicating they express Neu5Ac with α2,3 glycosidic linkage (Table 1
). These lectins showed an intense homogeneous binding pattern in all the olfactory structures, brain cortex, thalamus, and hypothalamus, but MAA only stained the molecular layer of cerebellum and the pyramidal layer of hippocampus. LPA and MAA intensely stained neuronal somas and fibers (Fig. 1
A,D), whereas glial cells only stained weakly. Most of the newborn CNS tissues did not, or at most scarcely, express sialic acids with α2,6 glycosidic linkage (Fig. 1B,E), except in the midbrain, cerebellum, and pons. Weak expression of Neu5,9Ac2 was found in neural bodies from olfactory structures (Fig. 1C,F), hippocampus, thalamus, midbrain, and cerebellum, but was abundantly expressed in endothelial cells of meningeal blood vessels. Neu5,9Ac2 was the only sialic acid derivative identified at the spinal cord, and exclusively at the dorsal white matter.
